{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01GbJBB2amS8wW7fRfokqdmF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XK4jq4wmsbpYCGNrui6Bag","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The test prompt used for behavioral verification does not embed phase-specific instructions copied from SKILL.md","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a static code inspection failure: either the test prompt contains hard-coded instructions or it doesn't. A pure in-process analysis of the prompt string content (e.g., checking that key phrases from SKILL.md are absent) is sufficient to catch this. No I/O, infrastructure, or model calls required.","test_description":"Static content analysis test that reads the test prompt string and verifies it does not contain verbatim phrases found in SKILL.md sections (e.g., specific phase instructions, terminology, or examples). Use regex or substring checks against known skill instruction patterns.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit level is appropriate; higher levels would be wasteful. The failure ('hard-coded instructions present') is deterministic and local to the prompt string.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The test invocation loads skill context from the plugin/skill files and validates behavior from that context rather than from hard-coded prompt rules","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is: 'skill context is hard-coded in the test instead of loaded from files.' A pure mock of the file-load function would pass even if the real file loading never works. You must verify that actual file I/O happens and the loaded content is incorporated into the prompt sent to the model. This requires test fixture files and wiring multiple modules together.","test_description":"Integration test that creates a test skill file (or plugin directory) with known content, invokes the test harness, and verifies that (1) the skill file is opened/read, (2) the loaded content appears in the prompt string passed to the model call, and (3) modifying the skill file content changes what the test loads. Assert the prompt includes identifiable markers from the test skill file, not hard-coded strings.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration is correct; a Unit-level mock would miss the failure if real file loading is broken or the loaded content is not actually used in the prompt.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"If the relevant SKILL.md section is removed or degraded, the behavioral test fails with the same user-style prompt","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior tests whether the test is sensitive to skill content changes. The real failure is: 'test passes even when skill content is missing, failing to detect regression.' To catch this, you must run the test twice—once with full skill content (test passes) and once with degraded skill content (test fails)—and verify the model's behavior actually differs. A mock model would produce the same output both times, hiding the failure. Requires real LLM calls to observe the behavior change that skill context drives.","test_description":"Agentic test that (1) runs the behavioral test with full skill content and captures the model's response (expected to satisfy the behavior invariant), (2) modifies or removes the skill content, (3) runs the same test with the degraded skill context, (4) verifies the model's response no longer satisfies the invariant (test fails). Document both model outputs as diagnostic artifacts. The test demonstrates that removing the skill content causes the behavior to regress, proving skill context is the driver.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic is correct; Integration with mocked model would always pass. System/Workflow not needed unless the test pipeline itself involves multiple subprocesses.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Raw model output is captured to a diagnostic artifact before any JSON parsing or extraction logic runs","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: 'raw output is not captured, or is captured after parsing has already corrupted/transformed it.' To catch this, you need to verify the artifact (typically a file) actually gets created with the raw, unprocessed model output. Mocking the file-write operation would pass even if the artifact isn't written in real execution (e.g., due to path issues, permissions, buffering). Integration test with real file I/O to a test directory confirms the ordering and the artifact's presence.","test_description":"Integration test that runs the test, then inspects a test output directory (or test artifact path) to verify (1) a diagnostic artifact file exists, (2) it contains the raw model response before any JSON parsing, (3) the file's timestamp or log ordering shows it was written before JSON extraction logic runs. Compare the artifact content against the structured/parsed output to confirm they differ (raw vs. processed).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration is correct; Unit-level mocking could verify the write call but would miss failures in actual file creation (permissions, path, buffering issues). System level not needed unless the artifact path is environment-specific.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Assertions verify structured behavior (for example field placement or schema shape), not mere keyword presence that could come from prompt echoing","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is: 'assertions only check for substring matches (e.g., `assert 'keyword' in output`), which the model could echo back from the prompt without understanding the concept.' This is a code-level inspection of the test assertions themselves. You can read the assertion code and verify it's checking structured properties (e.g., `assert parsed.field == expected`, `assert type(result.nested.property) is dict`) rather than substring presence. No execution, I/O, or model calls required.","test_description":"Unit test that parses the test file's assertion statements (AST analysis or manual code inspection) and verifies each assertion checks a structured property access (field lookup, type check, schema validation) rather than substring matching. Flag assertions using `in` operator on raw strings as failures. Examples of good assertions: checking field presence in parsed JSON, type validation, nested property access. Examples of bad: keyword search in raw output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit is appropriate; the assertion logic is static and local to the test code. Higher levels would not add value.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.87,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13249,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13249},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77516724-a643-48bd-b6ea-400851759ab7","uuid":"a44b0fcf-063f-4665-9e22-133a1df1c30f"}
